# DETAILED PROBLEM STATEMENT

## The Problem

SelfPM solves a problem of a lack of awareness, of why I kept failing repetitively at the tasks, seemingly so important to me. For years, I have known that I want to quit smoking weed, that I want to work harder, smarter, with a higher working ethic, and deliver my responsibilities in a manner congruent with how I imagine myself to work, to go to the gym, to eat well and nourish myself, to sleep with content, to not sabotage my day in ways that I am not able to achieve what I had planned. I kept failing. The same patterns would emerge.

I would make plans, I would 'prioritize', and then, I would fail at execution every.single.time.

I always thought it was the planning, that was the issue. It took me years to understand that execution is a science in itself. There are aspects to execution, like focus, patience, proactivity, discipline, accountability, that I was simply missing. This is what SelfPM helped me fix. It helped me execute my plans. At a high level anyway.

Deeper down, it helped me understand *why* my execution was failing. It helps me understand why I am not able to do the parts of the work I am seemingly SO WILLING and rearing to do.

---

## The Evolution: From Accountability to Observation

I initially created SelfPM to help me build accountability for my actions. In marking an update next to a 'KPI' everyday, I would be accountable to myself, to have gotten it done. I remember telling myself—I better do this, otherwise I'll have to face the version of me (accountant Kaushik) who takes account of whether it was done, and I'm going to be mighty disappointed in myself for doing something so 'easy'.

Turns out, that didn't work. Accountability is important in execution, but even before, it's more important to *observe*. To understand why things are not happening. So, I removed the 'judgement' from having to fill accounts everyday, in that, I stopped expecting that I will actually 'complete' the task. Now, all I was interested in, is just accounting for what actually happened, and reasoning why / why not I finished the task.

Removing the 'expectation' of accountability, to have to 'get it done', I was now able to freely enter my actual result without any judgement. I was just happy to get it done. I changed the 'accountability', from having to get the task done, to having to fill out my entry. This completely changed the dynamic. Now, I didn't care how well I performed. I stopped missing entering accounts into SelfPM, because I was 'scared' to confront the accountant, and 'scared' of surfacing my inadequacies. Now, I was so happy to just enter the absolute, brutal reality with radical honesty, in a way that allowed me to 'get points' for just adding my honest result. More points if I added context! Now, the game was to understand, not to execute, the performance WAS the accounting. I didn't have to fear it anymore, only the laziness to fill in the reality!

**At its core, SelfPM is a gap analysis tool.** It helps me understand everyday, why I am not able to execute a particular task that I have planned for. It helps me realize the 'gap' that existed—physical, environmental, psychological, nutritional—in my circumstances, that did not allow me to succeed in my pursuits.

---

## The Turning Point: CPO Analysis

I did this for 2 months or so. 70 days to be exact. Then, in a monumental moment, I exported all of my habit tracking data (results + context), into a pattern recognition LLM, and had it create my first ever 'CPO Analysis', essentially creating a 'psychological review' of myself and habits, based on the honest evaluations of my everyday efforts, I had collected over a period of time.

This was the turning point.

The analysis helped me reveal that I was struggling from a hidden saboteur—**Identity Pressure**. This pattern seemed to come up in my notes multiple times, as I recorded myself trying and failing at different tasks. I had often remarked that I would smoke weed because 'work was tough', or that 'I didn't play well', or that 'I had an excellent day, and needed to keep it up'—all indicators that I evaluated myself based on my worth to execute a task successfully, and the pressure of having to do it, and if I did, of having to sustain it, was causing me to cave, and to relent to avoidance behaviors, to 'soothe' myself and to 'take my mind' off it.

Incredible insight. Only could have been possible, if I had duly recorded honest evaluations, over this period of time.

---

## Understanding Identity Pressure

It helped me identify the 'gap' in execution. The gap being—'unresolved' Identity Pressure. This kept getting in my way, of executing tasks, by putting a very high tax on effort towards important tasks. Tasks / habits that would allow me to be 'judged' as a 'good / bad' person (I was good if I did tasks towards my goals, and bad if I didn't—a simple taxonomy I had created in my mind over a period of time).

All through my life, I have wanted to be 'extraordinary'. I have wanted to be more. And, I knew this was the path to do it. My family had their hopes pinned on me. I had my hopes pinned on me. I was never able to 'be like the other kids', or to 'have friends like normal'. I wanted to be more. And I knew, that every time I did an activity, that would put me one step closer to this 'extraordinary Kaushik'. I was scared shitless, if I would be able to succeed in its execution.

This was threatening my 'identity'. The fear of 'if I fail at this'—'I can't be the Kaushik I have decided I am, can't be the Kaushik I have shunned everyone else to become, can't make my parents proud, can't make up for all the times I've failed before'. This pressure caused insane paralysis, and never let me work on anything.

The times that I would execute, I would get more pressurized, thinking—"that's all I've done so far... now, I need to do this everyday, for a very long period of time before I can get anywhere—that's tough!". I would have a fear of success almost, in everyday tasks that required discipline. I am okay to do one-off tasks, in fact, I am very good at it. But, I cannot be consistent with anything. And this is why. I would be so afraid that I 'can't' make it all the way, and if I didn't, I would let myself and everyone else who believed in me down, and my whole life would not mean anything', and I would just let off.

This brings me to the next important aspect of what SelfPM fixes—**consistency**. It allows me to understand patterns, of why I fail to be consistent in my execution, and fix them.

