## What I Tried Before SelfPM

**'Oh, so much.'**

### Detailed Planning
For long, I have made detailed plans on what I'm going to do over the next week, month, 3 months. Very detailed plans, sometimes even indicating what time I would wake up and activities in 30-minute slots across the day. I always used to believe that if you fail to plan, you plan to fail. Turns out you also plan to fail if your plan doesn't account for the various pressures of execution, but I wouldn't figure that out until much later...

Each plan would add so much more identity pressure. Already I know that I need to do xyzzy tasks. Now, I have spent tremendous time and mental resources looking at calendars and making plans tight with others to make this detailed plan, which, most often would not even last a day, maybe 3 at best. This would make me feel even more pressurized because I'm wasting precious time on the 'Road to Kaushik'.

### Accountability Partners
For the longest time, I thought it was the habit itself that I was not able to 'do'. So, I was attacking each of the habits individually. I would try to have an accountability partner for the gym in my roommate, but turns out that added even more identity pressure (if I don't go with him, he'll think I'm a wuss/indisciplined, and will categorize me as such, and won't respect me). So, I stopped that engagement citing unrelated work pressures.

### Education-Based Approaches
I tried to stop smoking weed by learning all about the horrors of smoking, and the damage it does to your body and to your lungs. No avail.

### Overworking
I used to work into the night to 'catch up' on work, and 'do more' so I would be liked and respected—but, this only burnt me out even more, increased my overall fatigue and led to poorer decisions the following day.

### Habit Tracking Apps
I tried self-accountability apps—there's one with a penguin... Pingu? I don't remember, but apparently it's very helpful to help people maintain habits, by helping them track everyday. Again—it tracks accountability, doesn't enable observability—which is the core requirement I had in needing to understand myself. I didn't need another app to tell me I wasn't doing the right thing. I needed to understand why. So, in a month or less, this also fell off. I tried to get on it again, this time with a renewed enthusiasm to succeed, having made tall promises of international success if I just 'stuck with it', but also, to no avail. Failed being consistent a second time, and quit after ~40 days.

### Spreadsheets
Over the years, I have maintained spreadsheets to track my progress across everyday tasks. I have had some months where I track 7 metrics, some where I track 14 (didn't realize HOW MUCH MORE IP I WAS ADDING, EXPECTING SUCCESS ACROSS 14 DIFFERENT ACTIVITIES IN A DAY, WHEN I COULDN'T EVEN DO 3).

There were months where I filled in >80% entries, and there were entire months where not a single entry went in.

### CEO Supervision
I realized I was having trouble being accountable, to fill in everyday results. This is also when I was getting close to my new CEO. I was brought into this company as a 'prodigy'—a special assistant to the CEO to work on special projects, with him, all the time. So, I confided in him my struggles, and shared my spreadsheet with him, hoping that his supervision would encourage me to be more timely with my daily entries. This was still the time I was just doing binary accounting, no context.

Alas, this failed spectacularly. Now I was filling it regularly, but with bogus metrics. I would make them up everyday, so as to not look bad in the CEO's eyes. I don't even think he ever checked it, but now this became an additional burden for me to maintain. I just could not be honest with myself. So, I started maintaining yet another sheet, where I would try to be honest, and this sheet I would maintain for him. Truly a circus of events now that I look back.

### Gamification with Stakes
Then, specific to the weed, I made a deal with him that I would message him everyday, if I smoked up or not. We are both from the cricket fraternity, so I came up with a 'score' for everyday. I would get a run for everyday I didn't smoke, and lose a 'wicket' for everyday that I did. Man, only now I realized how much I have the capability to lie and bullshit someone, when I felt my image and reputation and 'identity' were at stake. I used to lie ever so often. Long story short—didn't work.

### Building My Own App (Steam)
Now that all of this was failing—I wanted to create an app for myself, where I would be truly honest. Still counting, not observation. I made an app called Steam with my close developer friend from my early startup days. It was just a fancy spreadsheet—allowing me to record daily activities. I even paid for hosting, so I thought—if I'm paying for this, I MUST take it seriously. Nope. Added more pressure to perform, didn't end up doing it.

**Which brings me to September 2025**—when I decided—I need to also account for WHY I am doing / not doing something. This is when the first hypothesis of 'why don't I try to understand my pain', instead of running from it came, and it has made a remarkable difference since.

---

## Why They All Failed

Each of the previous attempts, literally each of them—all did the same thing. They made me accountable for something I already knew I couldn't do. In doing so, they added MORE pressure to live up to an identity that was already being attacked, because of my inability to do the task. Each of these 'solutions' were actually just adding fuel to the flame, reinforcing to myself and others, that I wasn't 'capable' of doing the 'easy' tasks I have set my mind to. I am just another 'planner', without execution.

This judgement killed me. None of these solutions helped me understand the root cause. They tried to make me accountable for the symptoms, when I didn't even understand why they were occurring in the first place.

**Each previous solution made the problem exponentially worse by adding judgement and more pressure to perform.** Because I was just evaluating, publicly (even if in my mind, it seemed so loud, and... visible) all my flaws.

---

## How I Know This Problem Is Real

I lived it. For years, I was addicted to all kinds of avoidance behavior—weed, sexual releases, junk food, sleeping late, binging content, avoiding meaningful relationships because I knew I wasn't 'good enough', shitty performance at work when I am so good at it, dropping off my CEO's special assistant position and doing nominal work on the projects, losing out on friends who I didn't keep in touch with because I felt not good about myself (couldn't hold up to my 'identity'), poor performances in cricket because my anxiety was through the roof when I needed to perform, and what bigger performance than to play your favorite sport in front of your team, in a division 1 (local league cricket in Washington DC) setting? (I am a real good cricketer, but my performance last couple years has waned significantly because of this), missed gym sessions (even with a trainer, I kept up for a bit, then fell off), getting fat af, unable to maintain decent conversations with my parents—and a general hatred towards myself because of these actions.

Oh yes, the problem was real. No doubt about it. Still is in some parts.

